reviews: welcome to the top achievers group the group for blackbelts in the mt program we are a diverse group of educators from about countries we are lifelong learners who recognize that the more we know the more we realize that we don t know and we have the humility to admit so and are willing to continue to push the envelope to gain new mastery in our crafts the blackbelt program is really about being reborn you progress through the belts from white belt to blackbelt and when you achieve the highest level rd dan blackbelt you are back to the beginning from white belt to blackbelt to white belt again as if you are reborn tabula rasa you will find more information here https www millionteachers com wp content uploads document the black belts pdf and here https drive google com drive folders jgtjufdgffxkuzncypjxgbzzcoclejust like any good community we have rules and guidelines on how we are to relate with one another with respect and empathy conducting ourselves like the true professionals that we are we will refrain from sharing content not related to the program absolutely no religious and political posts will be allowed sharing of irrelevant links and spam is also not tolerated if you believe promotional material will be beneficial to the group please seek permission from either fatima or ishmael before posting borrowing from the the four way test a nonpartisan and nonsectarian ethical guide for rotarians to use for their personal and professional relationships we ask you to consider of the things we think say or dois it the truth is it fair to all concerned will it build goodwill and better friendships will it be beneficial to all concerned we will be self governing relying on every member to uphold and enforce the rules

reviews: my unalloyed appreciation to million teachers as an an organization i am inexplicably delighted to be a part of the million teachers community and project for the rare opportunity to learn it was brian tracy that said continuous learning is the minimum requirement for success in any field of life via the mt training platform i have been immensely impacted and more teachers in from my place of work are black belts as of present while some others are presently taking the belts the courses speak for themselves it s a life transforming adventure that has affected my approach to teaching and to life generally i have a better understanding of internationally approved contemporary teaching techniques and paradigms i now challenge my students to think creatively and critically to be emotionally intelligent and be leaders in their own domain there s more than words can say i am particularly thrilled by the grey belt which is about educational leadership as well as yellow belt where we have attributes of a teacher of course there s brainsprouting and trauma goes to school every bit of the belts was impactful thanks to mt i am a better teacher and a better person i have grown and i am still growing thanks to the journey so far i am grateful to the man who introduced me to this programme and community a man who grows and allows others around him to grow he is a rare breed dexterous vast energetic responsible intelligent vocal and practical a man who exudes excellence because to him excellence is not just an act excellence is a lifestyle the less said the better your reputation and result speak beyond what words can say i speak of no other than mentor morgan i am honoured to be an acolyte under your meticulous and thorough mentorship under your guidance i was nurtured to a rd dan award recipient thank you sir and without fail posterity will make demands on me in aeons to come if i do not recognize the brain box behind the million teachers project mr hakeem thank you for channeling your resources towards investing in people and education and for making these contents available to us one of the beautiful things about this is that we have a lifetime access to the courses and the websites thank you so much sir and i hope i will be able to do more not just myself but everyone graduand and award recipient once again i am grateful damilare akanbikwara state black belt graduand october

to all our new members welcome to the top achievers group the group for blackbelts in the million teachers mt program we are a diverse group of educators from about countries we are lifelong learners who recognize that the more we know the more we realize that we don t know and we have the humility to admit so and are willing to continue to push the envelope to gain new mastery in our crafts the blackbelt program is really about being reborn you progress through the belts from white belt to blackbelt and when you achieve the highest level rd dan blackbelt you are back to the beginning from white belt to blackbelt to white belt again as if you are reborn tabula rasa you will find more information here https www millionteachers com wp content uploads document the black belts pdf and here https drive google com drive folders jgtjufdgffxkuzncypjxgbzzcoclejust like any good community we have rules and guidelines on how we are to relate with one another with respect and empathy conducting ourselves like the true professionals that we are we will refrain from sharing content not related to the program absolutely no religious and political posts will be allowed sharing of irrelevant links and spam is also not tolerated if you believe any promotional material will be beneficial to the group please seek permission from either fatima or ishmael before posting borrowing from the the four way test a nonpartisan and nonsectarian ethical guide for rotarians to use for their personal and professional relationships we ask you to consider of the things we think say or dois it the truth is it fair to all concerned will it build goodwill and better friendships will it be beneficial to all concerned we will be self governing relying on every member to uphold and enforce the rulesthanks and welcome once again

state house press releaseosinbajo redefines social justice implications of climate change beyond reduction of emissions in public lecture at top canadian university vp says poor vulnerable in developing economies are least culpable but may be worst hit adds africa doesn t want free pass on net zero emissions targets there s sufficient evidence of climate sensitive locally grounded transition pathways beyond the reduction of greenhouse gas emissions globally efforts being undertaken to address climate change must also take into consideration its implications on social justice and inequalities especially for the poor and vulnerable in developing economies this was the submission by vice president yemi osinbajo san yesterday at a public lecture he delivered on africa and climate justice at queen s university kingston canada on the last leg of his day official working visit to the north american country buttressing his point on the concept of climate justice as a just and equitable transition to clean energy prof osinbajo stated that the notion of climate justice insists that in addition to discussions on greenhouse gas emissions and the need to reduce them we also recognize that climate change is an inherently social issue with important social justice implications continuing he argued that we need to reframe our climate action paradigm from merely a technical effort to cut emissions to an approach that places people and addressing social inequality at the centre of our efforts this is based on the reality that while climate change is already affecting every inhabited region across the globe and no place on earth will be immune to its effects the impact will be different across key regions and groups the vp pointed out that it is the poor and vulnerable largely in developing economies who will be first to suffer and worst hit by the effects of climate change even though they are the least culpable for the climate crisis according to him the point that must be made is that it is unfair that while many global north countries recognize the need for a wide range of options and different paths to net zero for themselves the same courtesy is not necessarily extended to africa the vice president added that clearly limiting the development of domestic gas projects which is a critical energy transition pathway for africa violates enshrined principles of equity and justice and poses dire challenges for african nations while making an insignificant dent in global emissions he further observed that despite contributing to barely of global emissions which is the least of any global region to emissions climate change as a threat multiplier is more evident in africa than in any other region prof osinbajo then referenced current estimates which posited that africa was warming faster than the global average and experiencing greater increases in the rise of sea level the sahel region has recorded vegetation loss leading to a sharp rise in conflicts between farmers and herders southern madagascar is experiencing what the united nations is calling the world s first climate change induced famine in nigeria we are currently grappling with the catastrophic effects of floods that have affected about states of our states displacing over million people destroying over hectares of farmland and causing about deaths the african development bank estimates that african economies are already between smaller because of climate change he observed with agriculture providing the largest number of jobs for many developing countries reduced crop productivity will worsen unemployment gaps on the continent and result in grave socio economic consequences prof osinbajo submitted adding that parallels of these multiplier effects can be drawn in other sectors from health to shelter and security although the vp noted that reducing emissions from the energy sector is crucial for limiting global warming the energy sector is one of the starkest examples of global inequality he therefore emphasized in the lecture that the energy needs of developing countries especially in sub saharan africa have to be taken into consideration especially by most developed countries in their discussion around climate change and a just transition for instance he stated that while sub saharan africa had about of its population or about million people without access to electricity in most developed countries have energy access he went on to point out that sub saharan africa remains the only region with a rising number of people without access to clean cooking fuels and technologies with of the countries with lowest clean cooking access rates in africa according to the vp clean cooking deficits produce devastating effects in sub saharan africa including millions of premature deaths from household air pollution annually prof osinbajo also noted that this electricity deficit has also worsened gender inequities as millions of women and children suffer from critical health conditions and half of secondary schools and a quarter of health facilities in sub saharan africa have no power he then predicted that because africa s current unmet energy needs are huge future demand will be even greater as populations expand for many gas rich but energy poor countries in africa such as nigeria we recognize the role that natural gas being a much cleaner fossil fuel must play as a transition fuel in the short term to facilitate the establishment of base load energy capacity and address clean cooking deficits in the form of lpg but there has been strong resistance to this several global north nations have placed restrictions on the use of development funds for natural gas infrastructure in africa with ripple effects in the private financial sector however in calling for climate justice for developing countries the vice president noted that one should emphasize that developing economies do not seek a free pass when it comes to climate action there is more than sufficient evidence of commitment to developing climate sensitive locally grounded transition pathways as many of us have done with our nationally determined contributions there are also regional initiatives like the great green wall initiative and the original vision was to create a wall of trees against desertification in the sahel the horn and across north africa but it has grown into a variety of sustainable land use practices designed to combat climate change and desertification and to address food insecurity and poverty the vp added that regarding nigeria s efforts towards combating climate change we have recently launched a detailed energy transition plan which outlines pathways to universal energy access by and net zero by as a global community we have to acknowledge the differences between groups in how they experience climate change ensure that processes for making decisions about the impacts of and responses to climate change are fair and transparent and determine how the costs and benefits of climate action will be equitably shared also speaking on the outcomes from cop in egypt prof osinbajo mentioned that a big win at cop was the loss and damage fund which is to compensate poor countries for climate change related loss and damage the vice president then listed what a just approach to global energy transition should recognize that developing economies must have universal energy access at levels sufficient for dignified livelihoods and economic growth that energy transition must place energy access for both consumptive and productive uses as well as the required policy flexibility financial and technical support at the heart of climate action that making capital available for the buildout of energy systems is central to reaching the goals of the paris agreement that to meet its decarbonisation obligations africa needs both conventional capital flows and the development of innovative mechanisms like debt for climate investments and carbon trading that we must lift inhibitive development finance restrictions and upscale technology transfers to ensure developing regions have access to the latest energy innovations and can build local industries on fair terms earlier in the day the vice president had met with principal officers of queen s university led by the interim provost and vice president academics dr teri shearer where he was briefed on some of the initiatives of the university including the one million teachers programme developed by the institution s former graduate student hakeem subair who also spoke at the event the one million teachers initiative is an education technology social enterprise startup which aims to attract and retain million teachers including in but not limited to nigeria and develop the capacity to train more in areas where classrooms are not available through its online platforms accompanying the vp to the university were the nigeria high commission to canada ambassador adeyinka asekun and his wife mrs olawunmi asekun special advisers economic matters ambassador adeyemi dipeolu social investments maryam uwais and other top government officials other queen s university officials who welcomed the vp included vice provost international and prof of history dr sandra den otter associate dean of teacher education dr peter chin assistant professor and queen s national scholar faculty of law dr oluwatobiloba moddy and other senior management staff established in queen s university is one of canada s leading research intensive academic institutions and is famous for its role in advancing the goals of the united nations sustainable development goals un sdgs laolu akandesenior special assistant to the president on media publicityoffice of the vice presidentth november

reviews: to all our new members welcome to the top achievers group the group for blackbelts in the million teachers mt program we are a diverse group of educators from about countries we are lifelong learners who recognize that the more we know the more we realize that we don t know and we have the humility to admit so and are willing to continue to push the envelope to gain new mastery in our crafts the blackbelt program is really about being reborn you progress through the belts from white belt to blackbelt and when you achieve the highest level rd dan blackbelt you are back to the beginning from white belt to blackbelt to white belt again as if you are reborn tabula rasa you will find more information here https www millionteachers com wp content uploads document the black belts pdf and here https drive google com drive folders jgtjufdgffxkuzncypjxgbzzcoclejust like any good community we have rules and guidelines on how we are to relate with one another with respect and empathy conducting ourselves like the true professionals that we are we will refrain from sharing content not related to the program absolutely no religious and political posts will be allowed sharing of irrelevant links and spam is also not tolerated if you believe any promotional material will be beneficial to the group please seek permission from either fatima or ishmael before posting borrowing from the the four way test a nonpartisan and nonsectarian ethical guide for rotarians to use for their personal and professional relationships we ask you to consider of the things we think say or dois it the truth is it fair to all concerned will it build goodwill and better friendships will it be beneficial to all concerned we will be self governing relying on every member to uphold and enforce the rulesthanks and welcome once again

reviews: to all our new members welcome to the top achievers group the group for blackbelts in the million teachers mt program we are a diverse group of educators from about countries we are lifelong learners who recognize that the more we know the more we realize that we don t know and we have the humility to admit so and are willing to continue to push the envelope to gain new mastery in our crafts the blackbelt program is really about being reborn you progress through the belts from white belt to blackbelt and when you achieve the highest level rd dan blackbelt you are back to the beginning from white belt to blackbelt to white belt again as if you are reborn tabula rasa you will find more information here https www millionteachers com wp content uploads document the black belts pdf and here https drive google com drive folders jgtjufdgffxkuzncypjxgbzzcoclejust like any good community we have rules and guidelines on how we are to relate with one another with respect and empathy conducting ourselves like the true professionals that we are we will refrain from sharing content not related to the program absolutely no religious and political posts will be allowed sharing of irrelevant links and spam is also not tolerated if you believe any promotional material will be beneficial to the group please seek permission from either fatima or ishmael before posting borrowing from the the four way test a nonpartisan and nonsectarian ethical guide for rotarians to use for their personal and professional relationships we ask you to consider of the things we think say or dois it the truth is it fair to all concerned will it build goodwill and better friendships will it be beneficial to all concerned we will be self governing relying on every member to uphold and enforce the rulesthanks and welcome once again

reviews: to all our new members welcome to the top achievers group the group for blackbelts in the million teachers mt program we are a diverse group of educators from about countries we are lifelong learners who recognize that the more we know the more we realize that we don t know and we have the humility to admit so and are willing to continue to push the envelope to gain new mastery in our crafts the blackbelt program is really about being reborn you progress through the belts from white belt to blackbelt and when you achieve the highest level rd dan blackbelt you are back to the beginning from white belt to blackbelt to white belt again as if you are reborn tabula rasa you will find more information here https www millionteachers com wp content uploads document the black belts pdf and here https drive google com drive folders jgtjufdgffxkuzncypjxgbzzcoclejust like any good community we have rules and guidelines on how we are to relate with one another with respect and empathy conducting ourselves like the true professionals that we are we will refrain from sharing content not related to the program absolutely no religious and political posts will be allowed sharing of irrelevant links and spam is also not tolerated if you believe any promotional material will be beneficial to the group please seek permission from either fatima or ishmael before posting borrowing from the the four way test a nonpartisan and nonsectarian ethical guide for rotarians to use for their personal and professional relationships we ask you to consider of the things we think say or dois it the truth is it fair to all concerned will it build goodwill and better friendships will it be beneficial to all concerned we will be self governing relying on every member to uphold and enforce the rulesthanks and welcome once again

reviews: i want to remember your face so that when i meet you in heaven i will be able to recognise you and thank you once again when nigerian billionaire femi otedola in a telephone interview was asked by the radio presenter sir what can you remember made you a happiest man in life femi said i have gone through four stages of happiness in life and finally i understood the meaning of true happiness the first stage was to accumulate wealth and means but at this stage i did not get the happiness i wanted then came the second stage of collecting valuables and items but i realised that the effect of this thing is also temporary and the lustre of valuable things does not last long then came the third stage of getting big projects that was when i was holding of diesel supply in nigeria and africa i was also the largest vessel owner in africa and asia but even here i did not get the happiness i had imagined the fourth stage was the time a friend of mine asked me to buy wheelchair for some disabled children just about kids at the friend s request i immediately bought the wheelchairs but the friend insisted that i go with him and hand over the wheelchairs to the children i got ready and went with him there i gave these wheel chairs to these children with my own hands i saw the strange glow of happiness on the faces of these children i saw them all sitting on the wheelchairs moving around and having fun it was as if they had arrived at a picnic spot where they are sharing a jackpot winning i felt real joy inside me when i decided to leave one of the kids grabbed my legs i tried to free my legs gently but the child stared at my face and held my legs tightly i bent down and asked the child do you need something else the answer this child gave me not only made me happy but also changed my attitude to life completely this child said i want to remember your face so that when i meet you in heaven i will be able to recognise you and thank you once again what would you be remembered for after you leave that office or place will anyone desire to see your face again where it all matters try to touch lives god bless you

reviews: to all our new members welcome to the top achievers group the group for blackbelts in the million teachers mt program we are a diverse group of educators from about countries we are lifelong learners who recognize that the more we know the more we realize that we don t know and we have the humility to admit so and are willing to continue to push the envelope to gain new mastery in our crafts the blackbelt program is really about being reborn you progress through the belts from white belt to blackbelt and when you achieve the highest level rd dan blackbelt you are back to the beginning from white belt to blackbelt to white belt again as if you are reborn tabula rasa you will find more information here https www millionteachers com wp content uploads document the black belts pdf and here https drive google com drive folders jgtjufdgffxkuzncypjxgbzzcoclejust like any good community we have rules and guidelines on how we are to relate with one another with respect and empathy conducting ourselves like the true professionals that we are we will refrain from sharing content not related to the program absolutely no religious and political posts will be allowed sharing of irrelevant links and spam is also not tolerated if you believe any promotional material will be beneficial to the group please seek permission from either fatima or ishmael before posting borrowing from the the four way test a nonpartisan and nonsectarian ethical guide for rotarians to use for their personal and professional relationships we ask you to consider of the things we think say or dois it the truth is it fair to all concerned will it build goodwill and better friendships will it be beneficial to all concerned we will be self governing relying on every member to uphold and enforce the rulesthanks and welcome once again

fall in hospital admissions from per day to about a day today with critical severe illnesses there has been a consistent drop in the positivity rate from a high of to an average of i appreciate the population for adhering to my directives resulting in the achievements above drop in cases positivity rates deaths hospital admissions government is following a multi pronged approach besides the lockdowns including mass vaccination of all people including those aged with the appropriate vaccines lifting the restrictions or not we must keep reminding people to do the right things and follow the sops the government does not just lockdown we lock ourselves down by being fakeall regional referral hospitals will be installed with gaseous oxygen plants we are targeting the production of oxygen cylinders per day the issue of oxygen will be solved from our experience with food distribution the cabinet decided to give the vulnerable with ugx beneficiaries were selected from administrative records several people are coming up with drugs locally we must protect the intellectual property rights of the scientists much of the proceeds should go to the inventors of the drugs the national planning authority has made projections of the situation and the likely outcomes based on scientists and npa projections directives are revised curfew time maintained at hrs pm to hrs am boda boda may now carry only one passenger but maintain sops strictly and stop at hrs pm kikuubo opens on conditions all kiosks should be removed roadside vending is banned and relocated only wholesale trade is allowed manufacturers should open up centres upcountry traders must revert to ecommerce arcades must follow conditions clear corridors adequate ventilation cctv cameras proper hygiene and registration of staff and traders burials should not exceed attendants until vaccination is sufficiently conducted weddings should also only hold people on the same grounds places of worship remain closed for days but online prayers are encouraged internationally accredited sports events allowed with no spectators with sops tests within hours before an event jogging outside is allowed especially if you have a face mask on gyms pool tables remain closed salons can open under strict sops and guidelines saunas are super spreaders so they remain closed schools remain closed until vaccination is sufficiently conducted moh should work out how to operate medical schools nevertheless learning should continue virtually reduction to of office workers can be upped to and with rd wave stay safe it s in your hands

the mentorship program is built on three key pilar increase gender awareness sensitization and education amongst teachers by leveraging resources provided by gr increase leadership abilities and success mindset of teachers by utilizes hp life and additional gr programming build a framework that allows mt to replicate and cascade the program throughout their entire organization across africa mentees become the mentors once selected to participate in program teachers have two pre mentoring assignments teachers must read and learn the hp life six leadership approaches see attached teachers in the program are required to take a short pre engagement assessment see attached that will help them gauge their level of proficiency in specific areas that pre assessment will then be used as a foundation to begin their mentoring journey the assessment responses will be shared with their mentors a special group of teachers where handpicked to also participate in the program as part of the mt program some teachers are selected to serve as learning hub coordinators these teachers play a crucial leadership role in facilitating learning hub activities and supporting the professional development of their fellow teachers once the lhc have gone through the program they will play a pivotal role in cascading the mentorship tool kit throughout all of mt additional teachers were selected based on their interest and engagement around the leadership development the teachers are female and male about the mentors original goal was mentors but due to overwhelming interest were selected the mentors are female and male mentors come from hp nigeria office hp us site councils and hp africa women s impact network cities include lagos abuja alpharetta houston boise palo alto san diego fort collins vancouver and south africamentors are being provided with resources and a framework to help steward the relationship and development of the teachers mentors are not required to have any specific technical background as the program is built around the establishment of relationships not a technical skillset the month curriculum for the program is as follows october teach girls bravery not perfectionnovember how great leaders inspire actiondecember grit the power of passion and perseverancejan female leadership and empowerment master class by lesley feb special feature girls rising contentmar mentorship in topics submitted by menteescommunication mentors mentees will meet for hrs a month hr bi weekly mentors and mentee will communicate via whatapp google meets and zoom mt has built groups within whatsapp and facebook for the mentees to communicate with each other and get additional resources hp has built groups within teams for the mentors to communication with each other and get additional resources live kickoff eventhappening in sokoto ni on thursday october th location time tbd mt is planning event

reviews: a man living close to me was scolding his years old son for not going to school seating down at home doing nothing hanging out with the riff raffs of our street he was so furious that he brought out koboko to use on his child as the man raised the koboko the boy held it in the air and he said in yoruba translation in english baba everytime you will be disturbing me to go to school go to school how many people have finished school without job in our family who are still poor mendicants wretched paupers and miserable beings by this time the father and the boy were still dragging the koboko before the boy managed to escape as he was running away from his father he said loud and clear that as for me ooo i won t waste my time going to school baba if i wait for a short time and didn t make it i will either do yahoo or money ritual what transpired between my neighbor and his only son kept me wondering for days i began to ask myself questions is education really the key to success in nigeria nowadays or one of the insignificant keys to success what kind of generation of young minds are we raising in the classroom this days how can a years old be thinking of money ritual or yahoo at this tender age of his life what has happened to our moral rectitude where did we lost it as a society what are we as teachers teaching these children in the classrooms are we giving them hope for a better nigeria or all we paint for them is a gloomy picture of a hapless hopeless and helpless nation if a years old can start thinking this way then we are seating on a keg of gun powder i am yet to recover from the incident so i have to share to lay it off my chest thank you james patrick

reviews: my experience as a teacher at the correctional centre i shukurat olowofela a guidance and counselling psychology student from lagos state university started my teaching journey at the boys correctional centre oregun lagos on may it was indeed an amazing experience i started with the illiterates and lower primary class which consist of pupils after i had concluded two class sessions with them i discovered that only fifteen pupils could write and spell their names correctly five of them were suffering from low self esteem which made them lose interest in learning with others and also changed their mindset about education negatively ten of them had dreams of becoming lawyers doctors engineers astronauts and even teachers in future if they are being able to get quality education and full support to fulfil their dream the first step i took was deciding to indulge them in counselling sessions with numerous word of encouragement success stories of prominent people ways to fight the phobia and different learning challenges as well as words that will calm their nerves and bring them closer to the academic setting and also introduce what education is and the benefit of them being educated after the counselling sessions took place for about three weeks we started with reading passages from textbook aloud and asking them to read individually so as to know who could read and where to start from for those who couldn t read i e teaching them how to identify and pronounce the alphabets as well as spelling their names the close monitoring through weekly assessments went on for about five weeks due to the fact that the syllabus ought to be used regardless in order to meet up with the scheme of work i decided to divide my two hour class into three in order to speed up the learning process the first session of the class was for dictation the second session was used for the mathematics class where i taught them how to read the time calculate money and some other basic calculationsand the last part of the class is usually interactive in order to get familiar with the pupil and to test how much they have learnt and what they have achieved academically in the centre reviews: ten mistakes not to make as a st teacher don t send a learner away from your class during teaching and learning as a result of bad behavior this is because you cannot account for what the student may be doing outside and this can count against you if an accident occurs don t touch a learner inordinately this is because the learner might claim he or she was abused either sexually physically you may not be able to refute it don t give assignments you don t have time to mark unmarked assignments or home work indicate incompetency unprofessionalism don t give emotional punishment to your learners it reduces their chances of becoming a better learner don t just teach within the period given to you especially when you are preparing learners for external examinations do create more contact time for your learners don t stay with a learner alone in a class laboratory office etc child s protection policy forbids it try and avoid one corner teaching don t ask a child to kneel down for too long a time he or she might have a health challenge you are not aware of don t conspire against your school head head of department academic head etc what goes around comes around don t be a difficult educator and avoid transferred aggression on any learner pocket your personal challenges and always be full of life don t treat learners unequally there should be nothing like favourite learner every child matters resumption tips copied

reviews: education is the jackpot for the poor why kids should go back to school uncle i don t think i am going back to school robert the kid i have been paying school fees for told me over christmas after sending me ugx i am making money why should i go back he asked i couldn t say thank you for the christmas gift of k it s so rare to get gifts from people you pay for but this one was making me happy and sad at the same time robert is the son of an ob who died about years ago and at the funeral i promised to pay school fees for the kid he has been doing well scoring at ple in a village school he was always the best in their class and covid found him in s he should be in s now but when covid struck he went home and got a job as a porter he earns about ugx per day to him this is a lot of money i used to give him ugx a term for pocket money now he makes that in a week he reasoned that if he continued working he would learn how to build and maybe become a mason one day i can become an engineer all brick layers are called engineers and look after my people and myself i understand his reasoning but i insisted he needs to go back to school without a father he is the beacon of hope at his home being the first born he has a lot of work to do it s important for him to choose the long winding road rather than a shortcut so we are still fighting i told him i have seen the magic that is in education in primary school i remember many kids who even us who were called the poor those that reported to school having been ridden to school on borrowed bicycles from over kms away some reported with a sack for a mattress and waited till the compound was cut to fill their specially designed bags with the dry grass to make mattresses for many the school shoes were the only pair they had and some didn t use them reserving them for their siblings now i see these same people in town as big people some who are hosted on tvs shake the nation there is one who gives the president ultimatums so often he is big this is because of education there is a doctor in mbarara and seeing him now you can t believe he has ever walked kms to school because of lack of transport education has done magic for those that dropped out the story couldn t be more different there was this classmate called joseph in p who had issues with mathematics when we started studying x and y he got confused and irritable one evening the teacher gave us classwork and asked us to find a solution none of us would find an answer it was raining and the teacher took a long time to come joseph grew impatient and stormed out of class and said we will call him if we finally find x he became a taxi tout recently i met him and he asked me whether we got x eventually i told him we did that same evening he was looking out of sorts just like many of the others that dropped out looking at your own obs you clearly see the difference school makes going back to school is the only opportunity for the kid of a wretched poor parent to step forward to grab his opportunity out of poverty it s an opportunity for that kid from the village to book a seat on the table of men in the city it s the opportunity for that son of a peasant to become a person they dreamed of being be it a doctor lawyer accountant or a big manager it s a bridge out of hopelessness to hope so if you have anyone around you that should be in school just don t listen to their excuses let them get back to school on monday let s do our part and pay school fees for robert and all others it s a worthwhile investment

reviews: touching tribute to our learning hub coordinators

i found this previous piece quite intriguing as it will be useful to orientate your students and teachers colleagues on our attitude towards education and learning in general schools just resumed and if you find it good and applicable you might want to read it on your assembly and explain were you deem fit enjoy there are three major people connected to your success in life and each person has a specific responsibility which most times can not be interchanged if there is a failure at one end then there will be a gap and it will be disastrous and horrible these three persons are listed below with their specific responsibilities your parents they are sadled with the responsibility of paying your fees hence you don t go to your teacher for your fees neither can you pay your fees as by right you aren t suppose to do if the fees are not paid nothing can be done for you even if your the best student in the class so your parents or the government in some cases must fulfil that obligation for your advancement the teachers these people are as important as anyone else in the chain of academic advancement as your teachers can t pay your fees so are your parents not sadled with the responsibility of coming to teach and make the research the specific job of the teacher is to make sure that learners understand what is been taught all the various technique and pedagogy employed by teachers have this sole aim if the learners don t understand then the teacher s job isn t done the application and synthetic analyses of information by learners is tied to their ability to first understand the different ways teachers can be sure that their job is done is by giving class works and assignments in different forms and variety which will be marked and corrected where needed all to ensure that learners understand the truth here is that any student that cheats or copies from another in class work and assignment or hides behind the crowed and pretends to understand or uses guess work has succeeded in vindicated the teacher because you can t score high in a test assignemt class work if it s a recorded test on a topic you don t understand this becomes a point of reference for the teacher should a learner fail the exam on same topic and probably similar question the learner won t be able to say the normal clich i didn t understand as the records don t lie therefore all teachers should seat up to this great calling to be sure that learners understand by all means possible emply all strategies and deployment all pedagogy just to make sure your learners understand and keep record of progress for reference and vindication it is called continous assessment the learner yourself you are the most important in this chain your major job is not to pass exams naaah it is never to have good grades surprisingly it is not to even come first in class neither is it to get a good job in the future your major job is to retain knowledge and improve understanding which will aid your application you can attend the best of schools and yet be a failure you can be taught by the best of teachers and yet be beaten hands down by a learner down town in less privilege school it doesn t lay on the lap of your parents neither is it on your teachers to help you retain what you have been taught it s on you as a learner doing assignment and participating in classwork class activities and so on is designed to help you retain knowledge and improve understanding which the teacher depends on to be sure his her job is done for conscience sake your studying at your personal time and prep are all geared towards helping you retain knowledge and improve understanding this is the work you must do towards your own advancement when this is done passing exams will be easy making your parents proud will be awesome getting a good job or building a company of your own will be possible your dreams will come alive and you will be fulfilled your parents have tilled the ground to pay your fees your teachers have read far and wide to harness the information broken down into scheme and bullets if at any point you don t understand what is been taught it s on you to ask and seek for answers no teacher should leave the class i don t mean the physical class when learners haven t understood what is been taught as the student is by right obligated to ask and ask and ask questions until clarification is achieved you start failing as a learner the day you let a lesson go without you fully understanding the lesson giving the teacher a false hope that you understand by cheating in assignment and tests or joining everyone to say the clich yes i underatand you have just made the teacher s job easy do your part my dear and wonderful great guys and your life will change trust me written by iro m u

reviews: interesting story that shows that teachers do make a difference keep at it on thursday one of my lecturers told a story one that changed his life academically he said when i was growing up i was so dull academically that no one bothered to check my position in my report card because we all knew that i d occupy no other positions than the very bottom of the class my father being a disciplinarian and an educationalist often wondered how such a dull child came from his loins he tried everything possible to help me changed my school almost at the beginning of every term yet baba tanda for out of each time result is called at the end of the term i was repeating class until my father decided to push me so that i could at least collect a certificate of attendance he had decided that i would go no further after that because definitely being a mechanic was my destiny because then only dullards were in that field once you see a mechanic you just know first hand that he is an illiterate in grade a miracle happened through the funniest way as the mathematics question paper reached me i read all the questions and started attending to the ones i thought i knew or had an idea of solving i was determined not to fail that very term i had cried many nights because of the humiliation from class mates family members and teachers i wanted that term to be different to atleast take a different position even if i go a number higher just a number i will be sooo grateful and i know it will surprise everyone and give all of us hope in me academically i got to this question that seemed simple and rushed to answer it but i discovered it wasn t as simple as it appeared the question was then the teacher supervising us further explained if i give you ten naira to share amongst your three friends how much will they get each i tried i really tried i used every formula i could remember even simultaneous equation yet there was a reminder of no matter how i tried was remainder i didn t think anything should be remaining hence i believed i was getting it wrong i was still trying to find what to do with the remaining when everyone finished and submitted the teacher had began to threaten to leave the classroom and not collect my sheets afterwards he even asked me what i know i was writing because if he were to be me he wouldn t border writing at all everyone laughed that statement and that laughter pushed in me the urge to prove them wrong so i decided i was going to solve that very question i dipped my hand into my knicker pocket and brought out naira i searched my empty locker for a cellotape i fixed the one naira at the end of the question and wrote a short note that says here is the one naira remaining from the ten naira after three people shared it i wasn t sure if i got the spellings correctly but i hoped the marker would understand i taped the together with the paper and submitted while i was doing all these the teacher didn t care to know why i was opening my locker as he would have if it were to be someone else he believed that i d still fail even if i was given a text book to copy from when i gave him the taped answer sheet he looked at me smiled and said silly two days later i was summoned by our form master after having a good laugh at me he told me that he could not ignore my zeal to pass even if he wanted to he offered to give me mins of his time everyday after school and i accepted that mins in three months changed my life academically at the end of the next term i took the th position nobody believed it myself inclusive my parents almost bought me a car the following term i took the nd position and the school shook to it s foundations my parents were invited to receive the report card themselves and ofcourse congratulations were in other for them as if they just had a child the school gave me an award of the most hardworking student my family organized a thanksgiving party the smiles on their faces made me choose the side i wanted to be on in life that of failure or success today i stand before you a lecturer who graduated with first class honors in civil engineering and law respectively all these because a man sacrificed mins of his time without asking for anything and did what we all thought was impossible the moral of this story is in every paragraph i did learn something i hope you did too copied

reviews: teaching learning technology digital education the observations or curiosity of mr vikas pota was apt but more apt was the words of ms giles who nailed it when she opined that the developers of education technology should ask pertinent questions and listen to what teachers were saying about what they really needed the technology players may be more concerned about possible revenue to be generated in the long run but for education technology to be truly value oriented then the opinions challenges and different needs of the learners must be thoroughly considered to be able to deliver technology of generational value a far reaching platform like mt who already initiated a movement to improve teachers capacity building on a scale never been attempted before removing all forms of boundaries barriers to international standard skills acquisition could be a good way to both learner s needs and feasibility study on what type of technology can achieve desired results in different geographical entity the common mantra for all producers is who needs what i want to produce answers to the above question show that the producer is more value oriented for the teachers to be effective in both understanding and deployment of such technology to attain goals targets with precision then the whole package must be total which means it should answer the following questions what are the general technological needs in enhancing learning what are tailored to meet special educational technology needs for certain learners challenge for example the braille technology for the visually impaired still can not be afforded by some schools be due to government action or inaction or lack of capacity on the part of the teachers training the trainers not just through online tutorials but the hands on experience cost implications mode of deployment finally the need for technological innovation or advancement in making learning easier can not be overemphasized because the world is evolving at a faster rate a practical example i decided not to enroll one of my daughters for early years education rather i inundated her with all forms of audiovisual from jolly phonics for beginners to age appropriate learning videos i took her to school last week then argument erupted with claims that she must have been in a school before because she was just way ahead of her classmates i could achieve that by harnessing what was already available online a partnership with t education would be welcome development morgan

reviews: mentoring the greatest act of leadership is mentoring if what you learn achieve accumulate or accomplish dies with you then you are a generational failure mentoring is the manifestation of the highest level of personal maturity security and self confidence an insecure person will never train people he will oppress people mature people create people greater than themselves your assignment has a shelf life you will die one day so train your replacement your greatest gift to the world is your mentee true leaders do not seek followers followers are attracted to true leaders the greatest obligation of true leadership is to transfer your deposit to the next generation leadership success is measured by the success of their successors no matter how great you may have been if you didn t produce a successor you are a failure you preserve what you built through mentorship legacy is about preserving all that you ve built by raising other people success without a successor is failure leadership that serves only its generation is destined to failure if your vision dies with you you have failed legacy is about living beyond your grave leadership is not a sprint but a relay the most important part of a relay is to successfully pass the baton on not running the ultimate measure of true leadership is not to maintain followers but to produce leaders true leadership measures its success by the diminishing dependency factor of its followers the ultimate measure of leadership is the ability to delegate tasks but not responsibilities true leadership makes itself increasingly unnecessary you are a successful leader when your followers can lead others your goal as a leader is to destroy the dependency of the people around you you are a great leader when your people don t need you make people greater than you and you will live forever true leaders do not seek power they rather seek to empower others never confuse your position with your value the ultimate goal of true leadership is not to maintain followers but to produce leaders the first act of a true leader is identifying your replacement and you begin to mentor them you become great by producing people greater than yourself when you produce someone greater than yourself don t get jealous when you train your replacement you are free to expand your work when you mentor people your legacy will make your tombstone unnecessary think about it rise by lifting others have a wealthfull season

reviews: resuming as a brand new teacher helpful tips first ask god for grace strength protection and guidance as we resume develop a positive mindset and be ready to handle the day to day challenges go for medical examination if need be treat malaria and typhoid fever before resumption first week of resumption is not too late it is necessary to acquire a daily dosage of anti stress multivitamins food supplemental drugs at least for days check your blood pressure regularly and act accordingly don t skip breakfast eat as a king or queen boost your immune system by eating fruits and vegetables daily or every two days be friendly with all forgive all make peace always avoid disputes and hatred during break walk out of your staffroom relax your muscles receive the fresh air and appreciate nature delegate responsibilities don t be jack create time for rest or sleep after work avoid excessive in take of alcoholic beverages be supportive walk up to your colleagues and students find out how they are holding up surrender all your burdens to the almighty he knows all that you need and he will supply all your needs according to his riches in glory remember that the teaching profession is not just an ordinary profession a teacher is a role model and destiny builder do your work diligently for only god can truly reward us god bless you all happy resumption great teachers

i made my second appearance on a local tv interview within a space of days here in kaduna state where i stay in my first interview i spoke on the importance of the girl child education been that my organization is centered on taking digital literacy education to the girl child from underserved communities and low income families in my second interview the presenter wanted to know why the boy child are left out in the society very well my initiative is centered on the girl child i could as well say that the advancement and education of the girl child somehow depends on the mind set of the boy child you may want to agree with me that we are in a male dominated society and the gender gap is too wide that we have to do something about it we spoke at length and at the end of my interview the presenter added that i am a motivational speaker well that also sounds good i might not have thought about it any way my name is adejoh idoko the founder girls for tech innovators competition initiative i am an educator a programmer web developer an sdg advocate and a cohort of hh ms ii sdg challenge you might want to still call me a motivational speaker just like the tv presenter maimuna abdulahi it is indeed my pleasure to be here amongst great minds thank you

reviews: press releasenpc recruitment portal circulating on social media is a scamthe attention of the national population commission has been drawn to the circulation on social media platforms of a fake npc recruitment portal inviting nigerians to apply for employment for the trial census and the census the commission wishes to state that this information is totally false and misleading and reviews: this is itall in one glance

a young man saw his primary school teacher at a wedding ceremony he went to greet him with all respect and admiration he said to him can you still recognize me sir i don t think so said the teacher could you please remind me how we met the student recounted i was your student in the rd grade i stole a wrist watch belonging to my then classmate because it was unique and fascinating my classmate came to you crying that his wrist watch had been stolen and you ordered all students in the class to stand on a straight line facing the wall with our hands up and our eyes closed so you could check our pockets at this point i became jittery and terrified of the outcome of the search the shame i would face after other students discovered that i stole the watch the opinions my teachers would form about me the thought of being named a thief till i leave the school and my parents reaction when they get to know about my action all these thoughts flowing across my heart when suddenly it was my turn to be checked i felt your hand slipped into my pocket brought out the watch and dip a note into my pocket the note read stop stealing god and man hates it stealing will embarrase you before god and man i was gripped with fear expecting the worse to be announced i was surprised i didn t hear anything but sir you continued searching other students pockets till you got to the last person when the search was over you asked us to open our eyes and sit on our chairs i was afraid to sit because i was thinking you will call me out soon after everyone was seated but to my amazement you showed the watch to the class gave it to the owner and you never mentioned the name of the one who stole the watch you didn t say a word to me and you never mentioned the story to anyone throughout my stay in the school no teacher or student knew what happened this incident naturally taught me a great lesson and i resolved in my heart never to get myself involved in taking whatever is not mine i thought to myself you saved my dignity do you remember the story now sir you can t simply forget this story sir the teacher replied i vividly remember the story that i found the watch in a pocket but i did not know in whose pocket the stolen watch was found that day because i searched your pockets while i also had my eyes closed in life we need wisdom for everything we do as parents teachers pastors leaders etc we should be able to close our eyes to some things not all misbehaviour require punishment some will need encouragement some mentoring and some monitoring be a teacher or leader who inspires not one who shatters copied

reviews: week challenge teacher how does a force effect a spring teacherschallenge the challenge teach and demonstrate to your students hooke s law using stanlab d virtual lab background how does the bathroom scale measure weight simple answer it s based on a simple principle of ut tensio sic vis is which in english is translated as as the extension so the force first discovered by robert hooke the bathroom scale shows the weight of the body placed on it inside the scale there is a mainspring connected to a lever and a rack there is also a pinion gear wheel when someone stands on the scale pressure is transmitted to the spring which then moves the lever the lever moves the rack which then rotates a pinion wheel and thereby rotates a dial which displays the weight of the person standing on the scale hooke s law is expressed f kewhere f force measured in newtone extension measured in mk spring constant measuring the stiffness of the spring and the unit is n mresources we have provided our d virtual laboratory app that teaches this experiment step by steplab manuala narrative storified explanation for this practicalvideo making resources and tutorials join our whatsapp telegram group and weekly ama to get the links to these resources main weekly prizes teachers will win n eachcommunity prizes teachers who have invited the most people to the challenge will win n eachthe major practicalobjectivesstep by step procedure of doing the practical using stanlabconclusionarts social sciences primary schoolwrite an engaging localised narrative story or develop other art media form poster animation infographics that teaches the concepts of hooke s law and its real life application introduction to the practicalobjectivesstep by step procedure of doing the practical using stanlabconclusionyour submission put up the video on any of these platforms instagram facebook twitter linkedin and tag us on instagram stanlab vr linkedin stanlab twitter stanlabhq facebook stanlabvruse these hashtags stanlab stanlabteacherschallenge stanlabexamprep mystanlabexperiencegetting your points viewscommentssharesput your students to work and get extra super points you get super points if your students download stanlab using your referral code and then carry out the experiments on their own and complete the student assignments all you need to do is post their video or end date th of august

up believing he can do what he likes you hear parent telling you as a teacher he didn t read anything throughout the holiday please help me ensure he reads in school my response to such parents is if you his parent cannot make him read how will i an ordinary teacher make him read as small as i am while growing up you get beaten by any elder that caught you misbehaving you hear i will beat you your employs him to teach one can t but wonder what the parent has actually taught the child my submissionthe children are innocent and should be treated as such questions that need to be asked are parent how well did you train your child government what program did you have for that child the same child that is supposed to be the leader of tomorrow teacher are you really a teacher and not a cheater copied this poem is dedicated to all teachersi m a teacheri may be a school teacher i may be a college lecturer i may be a university professor behind that doctor it is me a teacher behind that pharmacist it is me a teacher behind that engineer it is me a teacher behind that scientist it is me a teacher behind that economist it is me a teacher behind that lawyer it is me a teacher behind that political scientist it is me a teacher i don t qualify for a bungalow or a villa nor earn enough to buy an expensive house or a car like corrupt officers and corrupt politicians but yes i am a teacher some think or even say that i have too many holidays they never know that i spend those holidays by planning what and how i am going to teach when i go back to blackboard or whiteboard because i am a teacher on pay days i don t laugh as corrupt officers and others do but by the next day i love to come with a smile to those that i teach because i am a teacher the main source of my satisfaction is when i see them grow i see them succeed i see them having all those assets i see them bravely face the world and its challenges and i say yes i have taught in spite of living in a world opened by google because i am a teacher yes i am a teacher it doesn t matter how they look at me it doesn t matter how much more they earn than i do it doesn t matter that they drive while i walk because all what they have is through me a teacher whether they acknowledge me or not i am a teacher

reviews: crucial information for public consumption a lady s handbag which contained her cell phone credit card purse etc was stolen thirty minutes later she managed to call her husband from her friend s telephone telling him what happened her husband said i just received your text message asking me to remind u of your atm pin and i have replied a little while ago when they rushed to the bank the staff told them money had already been withdrawn the thief had used the stolen cell phone to text her husband and get hold of her pin within twenty minutes he thief had withdrawn her money from the bank account pls when sensitive information is being asked for through text message confirm by calling back also when being texted by friends or family to meet them somewhere be sure to call back to confirm that the message came from them if you do not reach them be very careful about going places to meet family and friends who text you please pass this on you will never know who this might help crime prevention unit

state house press releaseosinbajo redefines social justice implications of climate change beyond reduction of emissions in public lecture at top canadian university vp says poor vulnerable in developing economies are least culpable but may be worst hit adds africa doesn t want free pass on net zero emissions targets there s sufficient evidence of climate sensitive locally grounded transition pathways beyond the reduction of greenhouse gas emissions globally efforts being undertaken to address climate change must also take into consideration its implications on social justice and inequalities especially for the poor and vulnerable in developing economies this was the submission by vice president yemi osinbajo san yesterday at a public lecture he delivered on africa and climate justice at queen s university kingston canada on the last leg of his day official working visit to the north american country buttressing his point on the concept of climate justice as a just and equitable transition to clean energy prof osinbajo stated that the notion of climate justice insists that in addition to discussions on greenhouse gas emissions and the need to reduce them we also recognize that climate change is an inherently social issue with important social justice implications continuing he argued that we need to reframe our climate action paradigm from merely a technical effort to cut emissions to an approach that places people and addressing social inequality at the centre of our efforts this is based on the reality that while climate change is already affecting every inhabited region across the globe and no place on earth will be immune to its effects the impact will be different across key regions and groups the vp pointed out that it is the poor and vulnerable largely in developing economies who will be first to suffer and worst hit by the effects of climate change even though they are the least culpable for the climate crisis according to him the point that must be made is that it is unfair that while many global north countries recognize the need for a wide range of options and different paths to net zero for themselves the same courtesy is not necessarily extended to africa the vice president added that clearly limiting the development of domestic gas projects which is a critical energy transition pathway for africa violates enshrined principles of equity and justice and poses dire challenges for african nations while making an insignificant dent in global emissions he further observed that despite contributing to barely of global emissions which is the least of any global region to emissions climate change as a threat multiplier is more evident in africa than in any other region prof osinbajo then referenced current estimates which posited that africa was warming faster than the global average and experiencing greater increases in the rise of sea level the sahel region has recorded vegetation loss leading to a sharp rise in conflicts between farmers and herders southern madagascar is experiencing what the united nations is calling the world s first climate change induced famine in nigeria we are currently grappling with the catastrophic effects of floods that have affected about states of our states displacing over million people destroying over hectares of farmland and causing about deaths the african development bank estimates that african economies are already between smaller because of climate change he observed with agriculture providing the largest number of jobs for many developing countries reduced crop productivity will worsen unemployment gaps on the continent and result in grave socio economic consequences prof osinbajo submitted adding that parallels of these multiplier effects can be drawn in other sectors from health to shelter and security although the vp noted that reducing emissions from the energy sector is crucial for limiting global warming the energy sector is one of the starkest examples of global inequality he therefore emphasized in the lecture that the energy needs of developing countries especially in sub saharan africa have to be taken into consideration especially by most developed countries in their discussion around climate change and a just transition for instance he stated that while sub saharan africa had about of its population or about million people without access to electricity in most developed countries have energy access he went on to point out that sub saharan africa remains the only region with a rising number of people without access to clean cooking fuels and technologies with of the countries with lowest clean cooking access rates in africa according to the vp clean cooking deficits produce devastating effects in sub saharan africa including millions of premature deaths from household air pollution annually prof osinbajo also noted that this electricity deficit has also worsened gender inequities as millions of women and children suffer from critical health conditions and half of secondary schools and a quarter of health facilities in sub saharan africa have no power he then predicted that because africa s current unmet energy needs are huge future demand will be even greater as populations expand for many gas rich but energy poor countries in africa such as nigeria we recognize the role that natural gas being a much cleaner fossil fuel must play as a transition fuel in the short term to facilitate the establishment of base load energy capacity and address clean cooking deficits in the form of lpg but there has been strong resistance to this several global north nations have placed restrictions on the use of development funds for natural gas infrastructure in africa with ripple effects in the private financial sector however in calling for climate justice for developing countries the vice president noted that one should emphasize that developing economies do not seek a free pass when it comes to climate action there is more than sufficient evidence of commitment to developing climate sensitive locally grounded transition pathways as many of us have done with our nationally determined contributions there are also regional initiatives like the great green wall initiative and the original vision was to create a wall of trees against desertification in the sahel the horn and across north africa but it has grown into a variety of sustainable land use practices designed to combat climate change and desertification and to address food insecurity and poverty the vp added that regarding nigeria s efforts towards combating climate change we have recently launched a detailed energy transition plan which outlines pathways to universal energy access by and net zero by as a global community we have to acknowledge the differences between groups in how they experience climate change ensure that processes for making decisions about the impacts of and responses to climate change are fair and transparent and determine how the costs and benefits of climate action will be equitably shared also speaking on the outcomes from cop in egypt prof osinbajo mentioned that a big win at cop was the loss and damage fund which is to compensate poor countries for climate change related loss and damage the vice president then listed what a just approach to global energy transition should recognize that developing economies must have universal energy access at levels sufficient for dignified livelihoods and economic growth that energy transition must place energy access for both consumptive and productive uses as well as the required policy flexibility financial and technical support at the heart of climate action that making capital available for the buildout of energy systems is central to reaching the goals of the paris agreement that to meet its decarbonisation obligations africa needs both conventional capital flows and the development of innovative mechanisms like debt for climate investments and carbon trading that we must lift inhibitive development finance restrictions and upscale technology transfers to ensure developing regions have access to the latest energy innovations and can build local industries on fair terms earlier in the day the vice president had met with principal officers of queen s university led by the interim provost and vice president academics dr teri shearer where he was briefed on some of the initiatives of the university including the one million teachers programme developed by the institution s former graduate student hakeem subair who also spoke at the event the one million teachers initiative is an education technology social enterprise startup which aims to attract and retain million teachers including in but not limited to nigeria and develop the capacity to train more in areas where classrooms are not available through its online platforms accompanying the vp to the university were the nigeria high commission to canada ambassador adeyinka asekun and his wife mrs olawunmi asekun special advisers economic matters ambassador adeyemi dipeolu social investments maryam uwais and other top government officials other queen s university officials who welcomed the vp included vice provost international and prof of history dr sandra den otter associate dean of teacher education dr peter chin assistant professor and queen s national scholar faculty of law dr oluwatobiloba moddy and other senior management staff established in queen s university is one of canada s leading research intensive academic institutions and is famous for its role in advancing the goals of the united nations sustainable development goals un sdgs laolu akandesenior special assistant to the president on media publicityoffice of the vice presidentth november

reviews: to all our new members welcome to the top achievers group the group for blackbelts in the million teachers mt program we are a diverse group of educators from about countries we are lifelong learners who recognize that the more we know the more we realize that we don t know and we have the humility to admit so and are willing to continue to push the envelope to gain new mastery in our crafts the blackbelt program is really about being reborn you progress through the belts from white belt to blackbelt and when you achieve the highest level rd dan blackbelt you are back to the beginning from white belt to blackbelt to white belt again as if you are reborn tabula rasa you will find more information here https www millionteachers com wp content uploads document the black belts pdf and here https drive google com drive folders jgtjufdgffxkuzncypjxgbzzcoclejust like any good community we have rules and guidelines on how we are to relate with one another with respect and empathy conducting ourselves like the true professionals that we are we will refrain from sharing content not related to the program absolutely no religious and political posts will be allowed sharing of irrelevant links and spam is also not tolerated if you believe any promotional material will be beneficial to the group please seek permission from either fatima or ishmael before posting borrowing from the the four way test a nonpartisan and nonsectarian ethical guide for rotarians to use for their personal and professional relationships we ask you to consider of the things we think say or dois it the truth is it fair to all concerned will it build goodwill and better friendships will it be beneficial to all concerned we will be self governing relying on every member to uphold and enforce the rulesthanks and welcome once again

reviews: what does it do and how

my unalloyed appreciation to million teachers as an an organization i am inexplicably delighted to be a part of the million teachers community and project for the rare opportunity to learn it was brian tracy that said continuous learning is the minimum requirement for success in any field of life via the mt training platform i have been immensely impacted and more teachers in from my place of work are black belts as of present while some others are presently taking the belts the courses speak for themselves it s a life transforming adventure that has affected my approach to teaching and to life generally i have a better understanding of internationally approved contemporary teaching techniques and paradigms i now challenge my students to think creatively and critically to be emotionally intelligent and be leaders in their own domain there s more than words can say i am particularly thrilled by the grey belt which is about educational leadership as well as yellow belt where we have attributes of a teacher of course there s brainsprouting and trauma goes to school every bit of the belts was impactful thanks to mt i am a better teacher and a better person i have grown and i am still growing thanks to the journey so far i am grateful to the man who introduced me to this programme and community a man who grows and allows others around him to grow he is a rare breed dexterous vast energetic responsible intelligent vocal and practical a man who exudes excellence because to him excellence is not just an act excellence is a lifestyle the less said the better your reputation and result speak beyond what words can say i speak of no other than mentor morgan i am honoured to be an acolyte under your meticulous and thorough mentorship under your guidance i was nurtured to a rd dan award recipient thank you sir and without fail posterity will make demands on me in aeons to come if i do not recognize the brain box behind the million teachers project mr hakeem thank you for channeling your resources towards investing in people and education and for making these contents available to us one of the beautiful things about this is that we have a lifetime access to the courses and the websites thank you so much sir and i hope i will be able to do more not just myself but everyone graduand and award recipient once again i am grateful damilare akanbikwara state black belt graduand october
